While Polls have the Democratic Party Nominee clearly winning, there are two headwinds. First, the Republican President will challenge the legitimacy of the vote with broad accusations of vote fraud and vote manipulation. Secondly, while the Supreme Court has said states can discipline "faithless electors", those who do not follow the popular vote, few states have actually taken measures to protect the electoral college delegates voting in accordance with the people. There is a high likelihood of faithless electors (purchased surreptitiously by the Republicans) swinging the electoral college results despite the popular vote, making the third time the popular vote is not mirrored by the electoral college (all Republicans)

Statistical and betting market forecasts currently range from PredictIt (62%) to OddsChecker (67%) to PluralVote (69%) to NewStatesmen (87%) to FiveThirtyEight (87%) to TheEconomist (96%). While many are hesitant to believe the statistical models given the 2016 outcome, there is one notable difference this time: 2016 contained a higher percentage of undecided voters in the polls leading up to election day, putting Clinton under 46.0% in all but one of the ten closest states (that fact was aided by Johnson's presence, but that doesn't change the fact that the undecided percentage was higher at this point in 2016, and Johnson ended up getting only 3.4% on avg in these ten states vs. his avg polling of 5.6%, meaning Johnson was likely an effective "undecided" vote at that time for many of these). Biden, on the other hand, has above 46% in ten of ten close states as of seven days prior to election day, has near/above 49% in six of ten, and needs only four of those ten to win the election (ignoring special electoral districts, but similar story). Also, with Biden currently leading in the polls in most close states, mail-in voting and early voting are already well underway. It looks like voter participation will be greater this year, a factor that has historically favored democrats, partly because the increase tends to skew toward younger, often more Democratic, voters.

Two emerging factors that could unsettle all calculations in the next 10 days:

Current Real Clear Politics (RCP) polling averages show Biden has a 8-point led over Trump. At this same date in 2016 the polling averages gave Clinton a 5-point led over Trump and Clinton would ultimately go on to lose the election.1 While Democrats have been putting forth a strong showing in early/mail-in voting I do not think this significantly weighs on the side of a Biden victory given Republican mistrust for these voting methods.2 At present I simply do not believe Biden holds a commanding enough lead to indicate that he will be able to beat Trump in this upcoming election. I assess that Biden has a 58% win the 2020 presidential election. Trump has 41% and any other candidate has 1%. As of September 12, 2020, registered voters point toward a 53 to 45 percent spit between Biden and Trump. While this is a significant lead, other factors must be taken into account. 66% of Trump supporters say they support him strongly, while just 46% of Biden supporters say the same. 5% of Biden supporters, 4% of Trump voters state that there is a chance they change their mind, while 84% of Biden supporters and 85% of Trump voters say they are certain of their vote. Trump draws support from 53% of those with a high school diploma or less versus Biden with 89% of the black vote. Of all Trump voters from 2016, 94% say they will vote for Trump again this November; about 5% say they will support Biden. The pattern is the same as Clinton supporters will vote for Biden at the same rate. Research also suggests that voters are highly engaged, but nearly half expect to have difficulties voting. Another factor that has emerged to support a Biden victory is the new cohort of voters who have registered since 2016. In 2018’s midterm, nearly 120 million people voted, about 35 million more than in the previous midterm, in 2014, with 51 percent of eligible voters participating. This figure is believed to be 14 million new voters that were not voting in 2016. These new voters have also been primary democrat, pushing a 60/40 split. The Economist utilized analyzing polling and economic and demographic data to predict America’s elections in 2020. This algorithm currently has Biden with 336 electoral votes while Trump trails with 202. This model works by simulating 20,000 paths for the election, each time varying candidates’ vote shares to account for polling error, changes in turnout or the political environment, and the effects of campaigning. As of 25 September, the election has already seen 28 million ballots requested and another 43 million set to automatically be mailed. Democrats have accounted for over 1.3 million more of these pre-votes than republicans. BLM and the resulting call for social justice will also play a major part in the election as many of these new voters will be attracted by this rallying cry. On the other hand, It’s not just the BLM movement affected as every time there is civil unrest it attracts people from the right. This presidential election could be decided by the amount of violence in the street. Not just from the police and protesters, but right and left-wing groups that bring violence to the table as well. It’s going to be very difficult for the Trump administration to use the current status quo as a platform to win votes. Therefore, the factors and analytics suggest a minor victor for Biden in the 2020 election. To be as conservative as possible in my predictions, I continue to give the President an automatic 2 percentage point advantage in my popular vote and electoral vote modeling. In other words, I am taking current polling averages and assuming a 2 percentage point error, and allocating that to President Trump’s favor. That means if the average of polls has former Vice President Biden up by 8, I assume he is actually only up by 6. At the electoral college level, this means that for me to allocate a state to Biden, he must have a polling advantage of AT LEAST two percentage points. Otherwise I give that state to Trump.

Trump continues to rebound from initially poor COVID numbers. He has closed the gap in most swing states to within a few percentage points and while more states are 50/50 toss-ups than in 2016 it is still possible for Trump, as an incumbent now adopting a populist message, to pull this one out. Despite all of this, Biden continues to poll ahead overall and I still believe he would win if voting occurred today. With 2 months left, however, I am far from confident in either candidates' ability to win the presidency by a significant margin.

The polling reports are next to useless. In 2016 the polls were miserable. We know the problem is non-responsiveness by large portions of the electorate. This forces pollsters to adjust the sample results to correct for under sampling certain segments of the population. These adjustments are not reflected in the margin of error, they actually impact the probability of the forecast for the poll results being correct and it's usually not reported.

Which is very unlikely to increase, given the health crisis + recession. c) Related to above point, Trump was greatly helped in 2016 by facing a very unpopular candidate- which is certainly not the case in 2020. After Donald Trump's incredibly narrow win in 2016, the vote swing in US elections has been decisively towards the Democrats. For example in the key battleground states of Michigan, Wisconsin and Pennsylvania Trump won by 0.23%, 0.72% and 0.73%. All these states have experienced a swing of between 5-20% in favour of the democrats in the 2018 midterms despite the booming economy suggesting voter's do not credit Trump with the positive economic outcome. In addition, the most likely Democratic nominee, Bernie Sanders, polls consistently above Trump in these states as do other potential candidates suggesting the Democrats will probably win back these states barring an aberration. As well as this, other states the Republicans could lose include North Carolina, Florida and Ohio, potentially even Arizona, Iowa, Georgia and perhaps even Texas in an unusual election wave. This weakness in a large number of states gives the Democrats a large number of likely paths to victory. In contrast, the Democrats have few seats they are potentially weak in (due to only winning in 2016 by less than 5%), namely Nevada, Colorado, New Hampshire, Maine and Wisconsin. However, Democrats, especially Sanders poll far better than Trump in these states suggesting the chances of them being lost is quite slim. In conclusion, Trump support seems to have hit an early ceiling providing little room for growth over 2016. However, the Democrats possess large room for growth and the vast majority swing-states going into the 2020 election are currently Republican-held. In light of the current Blue Wave, it seems unlikely the Republican's will be able to hold enough states to retain the Presidency in the face of an energised Democrat vote and a potential candidate that appeals to the Rust Belt vote that catapulted Trump to the Presidency.

Historically, the incumbent President seeking a second term is likely to win (roughly 80% of all elections historically). The race will come down to "toss-up states determining the electoral college outcomes. The toss-up states are Arizona, Florida, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin account for 85 electoral votes. Democratic safe, likely, and leaning states account for 248 electoral votes. Republican safe, likely, and leaning states account for 205 electoral votes. With 270 electoral votes required to win, the Democrats need to gain 22 electoral vote while Republicans need to gain 65 electoral votes. In the current analysis, the Republicans "must" win Florida in order to have a winning path forward. If the Democrats win the electoral college in any one of the other toss-up states (Arizona, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, or Wisconsin) the Republicans would need to run the table on the remainder in addition to Florida. A single electoral vote from Nebraska's 2nd district is generally considered a toss-up, however for this analysis, it was conceded into the Republican column reflecting the otherwise safe status of the balance of the state. If one were to consider Michigan, Nevada, and New Hampshire as tossups the Democrats sit at 222 electoral votes (48 more needed) and the Republicans sit at 204 (66 more needed) electoral votes.
